    "abstract": "<jats:p>We develop a theory of monotone comparative statics for models with adjustment costs. We show that comparative\u2010statics conclusions may be drawn under the usual ordinal complementarity assumptions on the objective function, assuming very little about costs: only a mild monotonicity condition is required. We use this insight to prove a general Le Chatelier principle: under the ordinal complementarity assumptions, if short\u2010run adjustment is subject to a monotone cost, then the long\u2010run response to a shock is greater than the short\u2010run response. We extend these results to a fully dynamic model of adjustment over time: the Le Chatelier principle remains valid, and under slightly stronger assumptions, optimal adjustment follows a monotone path. We apply our results to models of saving, production, pricing, labor supply, and investment.</jats:p>",
